NEW ORLEANS A federal
appeals court has ruled unconsti-
tutional a federal law penalizing
US. citizens for leaving and
re-entering the country without a
valid passport.


"The government cannot say to
its citizen, standing beyond its
border, that his re-entry into the
land of his allegiance Is a GRIM
inal offense," the 5th US. Cir
cult Court Of Appeals said.


A three-judge appellate court
panel threw out a lower federal
court conviction of Negro jour-
nalist William Worthy for al
legedly illegally re-entering the
United States after going to Cuba
in 1861.

Coins Passport
Rights Again

SAN DIEGO. Calf. Archie
Moore. former world light
heavyweight boxing champion.
and friend we're injured in a
head-on, two-car collision on
US. l0l at the San Diego River
Bridge.


The car Moore was driving
plunged down a 10 foot bank.


Moore, of San Diego, and his
friend, Charles Payne, "a, of
Toledo, Ohio. were reported in
good condition at Doctors Hos
pital despite back and leg in
juries.


The occupant of the other car,
Pvt. Eddie Wallace Jr., 10, Camp
Pendleton, was unhurt.

BOXER ARCHIE
MOORE HURT

NEW YORK The NAACP has
asked the Cincinnati-based
Brunswick Corporation, manu-
facturers of sporting goods, to
reconsider its proposed plan to
close one or both of its Cincin-
natl plants and transfer opera
lions to Albany. Ca, where the
corporation already maintains a
factory.


In letter to James Nelson,
the corporations general mana
ger, John A. Morsell. assistant
to NAACP Executive Secretary
Roy wilkins, expressed "pro-
found dismay at the prospect Of
such a move"


Mr.. Morsell's letter, dated
March S, and made public here
today, cited "the tense and ex-
plosive racial situation in Al
bany :. and the long history Of
calculated and brutal violation
of democratic rights which the
authorities there have inflicted
upon the citys Negro popula-
ton"


Similar patterns of racial re-
preston in a number of southern
localities, Mr.. Morsell warned.
"have produced the inevitable
reaction on the part Of Negroes
and the result has been intensi-
fled racial unrest, demonstra-
lions, consumer boycotts and
sometimes even more recent
challenges of the status quo"


Elsewhere the NAACP spokes-
man pointed out. zone of the re-
suits of this kind Of development
has been the cancellation or re-
consideration Of corporate plans
for relocation in the South, since
a stable productive environment
is obviously An important asset.

NAACP URGES FIRM
TO STAY IN NORTH

PRINCETON, N. J. = Norman
Thomas, the 79-year-old Social
list, said Negroes we're making
a mistake demanding preferential
treatment from employers.


"In view of the past" he
said eff the Negro and white
are equally qualified the employ
err should hire the Negro but it
has been a mistake to talk Of
preferential employment"

Socialist Head Says
Negroes Are Wrong

SAN FRANCISCO = Police ar
rested more than 100 pickets who
went inside the Cadillac show
rooms and refused to leave.


The pickets, spoons ored by the
Congress of Racial Equality. have
charged that the General Motors
operation Disseminated against
hiring Negroes.


Denying the charges, General
Motors said in a statement it
had to take steps Ito prevent
what amounts to illegal seizure
of its property"

PICKE1S ARRESTED AT
CADILLAC SHOWROOM

PHILADELPHIA = The Oppor-
tunities NATURALIZATION Center,
designed to train Negroes for
technical employment, has re-
ceived a 100000 grant from the
Philadelphia Council for Com
munity Advancement.


The center, described as the
first project of its kind by a
Negro community in the United
States, began job-training clas-
ses in a former police station
last week.


Samuel Dash, executive direc-
tor of the council, which receives
most of its money from the Ford
Foundation, said his group would
seek additional funds for the pro-
iect from the Federal Govern
ment.


The Rev. Leon H. Sullivan,
board chairman of the center,
said the grant brought total con-
tributions in equipment and cash
gifts to more than 100000. He
said the center would have more
than 800 persons in training pro-
grams next month and expected
to provide instruction for at least
$50 persons before the end of
the year.

Land will be shown by Mrs. Es-
telle Burnett at Phillips CINE
Church, 18th and E. Adams, Sum-,
Mar. y at 8 pm. There will be
no charge.


The program is spoons ored by
the Senior Usher Board and the
Guiding Light Society.

Holy Land Films
To Be Shown

Rev. Jerry w. Ford, Of Los
Angeles, former Phoenix pastor
will conduct a preaching mission
at Tanner Chapel AME Church,
9th and E. Jefferson, Mar. 22-28.


Easter sunrise services will be
held at the church Sum-, Mar. %
starting at E am.

TO APPEAR HERE

gram progress 100 years after emancipation
Phoenix Baptist Church. 10th and E. Broadway

and c. N. Hall presented the
gram.
